The paper discusses the competition and selection of conventions in the online domain, specifically in the e-print arXiv. The paper focuses on the spread of low-level authoring conventions, which suggests a focus on the technical aspects of computer science (cs). The use of macros and author-defined conventions also suggests a focus on natural language processing (cs.CL) and digital libraries (cs.DL). The analysis of the interaction among co-authors and the distinction between more and less experienced members of the community suggests a focus on human-computer interaction (cs.HC) and social computing (cs.CY). Overall, the paper's content and methodology suggest that it is most likely to belong to the cs.SI (social and information networks) sub-category, with cs.CL, cs.CY, cs.DL, and cs.HC as secondary possibilities.
